 <p></p><i></i></td></tr><tr bgcolor=#000000><td nowrap width=20% valign=top align=left><span class=title> <A HREF=http://pub54.ezboard.com/ushunyaatma.showPublicProfile?language=EN>shunyaatma</A></span><br> <span class=usertitle>Froglok Guk Knight</span><br>  Posts: 3<br> <font color=#00CCFF>(2/26/02 5:55:19 am)</font><br>   <a href=http://pub54.ezboard.com/fquelliousquaterstherebirthfrm13.showAddReplyScreenFromWeb?topicID=203.topic&index=16>Reply</a>   </td><td valign=top align=left class=m><span class=title> Re: Ragefire Solution</span><hr size=1> Answers based on info acquired from Xeik, the server GM (I grilled him pretty bad, because I myself wanted to know what was acceptable and unacceptable to the final dispute reckoners.)<br>
<br>
<br>
Q) In GM # 5, if the first attempt fails, but no one else engages the mob while the first triggering group recovers, can the first group re-engage when ready or do they have to wait on anyone else who wants to take a turn before taking another shot?<br>
<br>
A.) If the first force is recooperated, ready, and able to kill and the second one is not completely or very nearly ready (like 5-10 mins from away from readiness) then yes, they may go again.  If the second force is completely ready and able to kill (in which case they probably would have immediately engaged it upon the disengagement of the first force), then no, the first force must wait their turn (and they probably won't get one, but you never know).<br>
<br>
Q.) Also, does the triggering aspect completely disappear as soon as the first group dis-engages or is that still a consideration if they are ready to re-engage and the dragon has not been engaged by another group yet?&lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
A.) I'm not sure what triggering aspect you're talking about.  The skyfire spawn requires no trigger component so in failure, nothing is lost item-wise.<br>
<br>
Q.) What is &quot;fail&quot;? Is it merely the reduction of your killing force to the point that the kill is not possibile (only feigners or offline rezzers left alive, no one dealing damage)? Does &quot;failure&quot; only come when the attackers cry &quot;Uncle&quot; and leave?&lt;&lt;<br>
<br>
A.) It would be the first case.  Failure means the mob is disengaged.  For example, if all that's left is feigners, camped out clerics, and a bard or druid kiting around Ragefire (remember kiting does not count as engagement) til the force can recoop, they have failed and their turn is over.<br>
<br>
Hope that helps.<br>
<br>
Answer<br>
60 Cleric<br>
Vis Maior<br>
